# Playwright Conventions

- **Locators** — role/label first; testid escape hatch; never CSS/XPath
- **Waiting** — web-first assertions only; never `waitForTimeout`
- **Page Objects** — one per page; locators in constructor; no assertions in POMs
- **Auth** — `storageState` via the setup project; API-login for speed
- **Data** — Faker factories under `test-data/`; every test cleans up after itself
- **Tags** — exactly one of `@smoke` `@sanity` `@regression` `@api` `@e2e` `@destructive`
- **API** — `request` fixture for setup/teardown and contract checks
- **Mocking** — `route`/`fulfill` for 500/503/timeout/empty/malformed
- **Accessibility** — axe scan (wcag2a/aa) on key pages + a keyboard-nav check
- **Assertions** — web-first; soft for multi-check; visual where it earns it
- **Anti-flake** — CI-only retries; isolation; `page.clock`; pinned locale/timezone

Each rule below shows the standard, then a ✅ good and ❌ bad example. When in doubt, prefer the example a *user* (or a screen reader) would recognize over the one coupled to markup.

## 1. Locators — user-facing, in priority order

Reach for locators top-to-bottom: `getByRole` → `getByLabel`/`getByPlaceholder` → `getByText` → `getByTestId` → (last resort) CSS/XPath, flagged for review.

✅ **Good**

```ts
await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'New Program' }).click();
await page.getByLabel('Program Name').fill('Web Development 2026');
await page.getByRole('row', { name: /Web Development 2026/ }).getByRole('button', { name: 'Edit' }).click();
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
await page.locator('.btn.btn-primary').click();            // couples to CSS classes
await page.locator('#root > div > div:nth-child(3) input').fill('x'); // breaks on any layout change
await page.locator('//button[2]').click();                 // XPath by position — meaningless and brittle
```

**Why:** role/label locators survive restyling and refactors, and they double as an accessibility check — if `getByRole('button', { name: 'Create' })` finds it, the control has an accessible name. `getByTestId` is the escape hatch when nothing user-facing fits; CSS/XPath is a smell.

## 2. Waiting — web-first assertions only, never fixed timeouts

Never `waitForTimeout`. `expect()` retries until the condition holds or the timeout expires.

✅ **Good**

```ts
await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Save' }).click();
await expect(page.getByText('Program updated')).toBeVisible();
await expect(page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Save' })).toBeEnabled();
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Save' }).click();
await page.waitForTimeout(2000);                 // a bet: too short = flaky, too long = slow
expect(await page.getByText('Program updated').isVisible()).toBe(true); // snapshot, no retry
```

**Why:** a fixed wait guesses a duration; a web-first assertion waits for *reality*. `isVisible()` returns a boolean once and never retries — use `expect(locator).toBeVisible()` instead.

## 3. Page Object Model — locators in, assertions out

One POM per page/component in `pages/`. Locators live in the constructor; methods perform user actions; **no assertions in a POM** — those belong in the test, which describes intent.

✅ **Good**

```ts
// pages/components/new-program.modal.ts
export class NewProgramModal {
  constructor(private page: Page) {}
  readonly name = this.page.getByRole('textbox', { name: 'Program Name' });
  readonly create = this.page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Create' });

  async createProgram(name: string) {
    await this.name.fill(name);
    await this.create.click();
  }
}

// tests/ds1-create-program.spec.ts
await modal.createProgram(unique('Web Dev'));
await expect(programs.row(name)).toBeVisible();        // assertion lives in the test
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
export class NewProgramModal {
  async createProgram(name: string) {
    await this.page.fill('#name', name);
    await this.page.click('.submit');
    await expect(this.page.getByText('created')).toBeVisible(); // assertion buried in the POM
  }
}
```

**Why:** assertions in POMs hide what a test verifies and make POMs un-reusable across tests that expect different outcomes. The test should read like the intent; the POM is the *how*.

## 4. Auth — log in once with storageState; never per test

Authenticate once in the setup project, save `storageState`, and let every test inherit it. Use API login when the UI login isn't what's under test.

✅ **Good**

```ts
// tests/auth.setup.ts
setup('authenticate', async ({ page }) => {
  const login = new LoginPage(page);
  await login.login(process.env.DIDAXIS_EMAIL!, process.env.DIDAXIS_PASSWORD!);
  await expect(new DashboardPage(page).heading).toBeVisible();
  await page.context().storageState({ path: 'playwright/.auth/user.json' });
});
// config: main project has dependencies: ['setup'], use: { storageState: 'playwright/.auth/user.json' }
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test.beforeEach(async ({ page }) => {       // logs in before EVERY test — slow, flaky
  await page.goto('/login');
  await page.getByLabel('Email').fill('admin@didaxis.studio'); // hardcoded credential
  await page.getByLabel('Password').fill('hunter2');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign In' }).click();
});
```

**Why:** per-test UI login multiplies runtime and adds a flaky dependency to every test. The auth file is git-ignored and regenerated each run (locally and in CI). Credentials come from `process.env`, never hardcoded.

## 5. Test data — unique, self-cleaning, isolated

Every test creates its own data with a unique name and cleans up after itself. Tests must not depend on each other or on leftover state.

✅ **Good**

```ts
const unique = (p: string) => `${p}-${Date.now()}`;

test('creates a program', async ({ page, request }) => {
  const name = unique('Web Dev');
  // ... create via UI ...
  await expect(list.row(name)).toBeVisible();
});

test.afterEach(async ({ request }) => {
  await cleanupProgramsByPrefix(request, 'Web Dev-');   // API teardown
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test('creates a program', async ({ page }) => {
  await form.createProgram('Web Development');   // same name every run → collides on 2nd run
});                                              // no cleanup → pollutes the next run / CI
```

**Why:** shared or static data makes tests order-dependent and flaky in parallel. `Date.now()` keeps names unique; API cleanup is faster and more reliable than clicking through the UI.

## 6. API testing — use the `request` fixture for setup, teardown, and contracts

Use the API for state you don't want to build through the UI, for teardown, and for contract checks. Mix API setup with UI assertions to keep tests fast and focused.

✅ **Good**

```ts
test('list shows a program created via API', async ({ page, request }) => {
  const res = await request.post('/api/programs', { data: { name: unique('API Prog') } });
  expect(res.ok()).toBeTruthy();
  const { id, name } = await res.json();
  await page.goto('/programs');
  await expect(page.getByRole('row', { name })).toBeVisible();
  await request.delete(`/api/programs/${id}`);    // teardown via API
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test('list shows a program', async ({ page }) => {
  // builds 10 prerequisite programs by clicking through the UI — slow and fragile
  for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) await form.createProgram(`Prog ${i}`);
});
```

**Why:** the UI is for testing the UI, not for manufacturing prerequisite data. API setup/teardown is an order of magnitude faster and far less flaky.

## 7. Network mocking — make edge cases deterministic

Mock the failures you can't trigger on demand: `500`, `503`, timeout, empty list, malformed payload, slow response. Mock the case you're forcing — never mock the thing you're trying to test.

✅ **Good**

```ts
test('shows an error when save fails', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.route('**/api/programs', route =>
    route.fulfill({ status: 503, body: 'Service Unavailable' }));
  await form.createProgram(unique('Web Dev'));
  await expect(page.getByText('Something went wrong')).toBeVisible();
});

test('handles an empty list', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.route('**/api/programs', route =>
    route.fulfill({ status: 200, body: '[]' }));
  await page.goto('/programs');
  await expect(page.getByText('No programs yet')).toBeVisible();
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test('create works', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.route('**/api/programs', route =>
    route.fulfill({ status: 200, body: JSON.stringify({ id: 1, name: 'x' }) }));
  await form.createProgram('x');                 // mocks the very endpoint under test → proves nothing
  await expect(page.getByText('created')).toBeVisible();
});
```

**Why:** happy-path tests prove the app works when the server behaves; mocking proves it survives when the server misbehaves — which production guarantees. Use `routeFromHAR` to replay a recorded session when you need realistic payloads.

## 8. Accessibility — axe is the floor, keyboard + names are the rest

Run an automated scan on key pages, and add the checks axe can't make: keyboard operability and accessible names. Axe catches roughly a third of issues; you own the other two-thirds.

✅ **Good**

```ts
import AxeBuilder from '@axe-core/playwright';

test('programs page has no a11y violations', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/programs');
  const results = await new AxeBuilder({ page }).withTags(['wcag2a', 'wcag2aa']).analyze();
  expect(results.violations).toEqual([]);
});

test('new-program flow is keyboard operable', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/programs');
  await page.keyboard.press('Tab');
  await expect(page.getByRole('button', { name: 'New Program' })).toBeFocused();
  await page.keyboard.press('Enter');
  await expect(page.getByRole('dialog', { name: 'New Program' })).toBeVisible();
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test('page looks fine', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/programs');
  // eyeballed once in dev; no scan, no keyboard path, no assertion
});
// or: an icon-only button with no accessible name —
await page.locator('button.icon-edit').click();   // getByRole('button', { name: 'Edit' }) would FAIL here, which is the bug
```

**Why:** a control a screen reader can't name is broken the same way a 500 is broken — you just had no test that noticed. If your `getByRole(... name ...)` locators work, your accessible names are sane; if they don't, that failure *is* the accessibility bug. Scope scans with `.include()/.exclude()` for third-party widgets.

## 9. Assertions — web-first by default, soft for multi-check, visual where it earns it

Prefer auto-retrying web-first assertions. Use `expect.soft` to collect several checks in one run. Use visual snapshots sparingly, masking dynamic regions.

✅ **Good**

```ts
// collect all failures instead of stopping at the first
await expect.soft(page.getByRole('heading', { name: 'Programs' })).toBeVisible();
await expect.soft(page.getByRole('button', { name: 'New Program' })).toBeEnabled();

// visual, with dynamic content masked
await expect(page).toHaveScreenshot('programs.png', {
  mask: [page.getByRole('cell', { name: /Updated/ })],
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
const text = await page.getByRole('heading').textContent();
expect(text).toContain('Programs');               // no retry; races the render

await expect(page).toHaveScreenshot();             // unmasked timestamps → fails every run
```

**Why:** non-retrying assertions race the UI; web-first assertions wait. Unmasked visual snapshots flake on any dynamic content. Soft assertions turn three reruns into one informative failure.

## 10. Anti-flake — flake is a configuration choice

Retries in CI only, full isolation, pinned locale/timezone, controlled time, trace on failure.

✅ **Good**

```ts
// playwright.config.ts
const isCI = !!process.env.CI;

export default defineConfig({
  fullyParallel: true,
  retries: isCI ? 1 : 0,                  // local runs fail loudly; CI tolerates a transient blip
  use: {
    baseURL: process.env.DIDAXIS_URL,
    trace: isCI ? 'retain-on-failure' : 'on',
    locale: 'en-CA',                       // recommended — kills date/locale flake
    timezoneId: 'America/Toronto',
  },
});

// freeze time so a "created 2 minutes ago" label is deterministic
await page.clock.install({ time: new Date('2026-06-08T12:00:00') });
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
export default defineConfig({
  retries: 5,                              // hides real flake behind brute force
  workers: 1,                              // serial "fix" for tests that share state
});
// tests that read `new Date()` and assert on "today" → break at midnight / across timezones
```

**Why:** retries buy a green build, not a fixed one — a test that only passes on retry is a bug with a snooze button; track those. Pinned locale/timezone and `page.clock` remove whole classes of time-dependent flake. Cranking `workers: 1` to stop collisions hides the real problem: tests that aren't isolated. Use `npm run test:destructive` (`--workers=1`) only for the `@destructive` slice that truly mutates shared state.

## 11. Tags — exactly one per test

Tag each `test(...)` with **exactly one** of:

| Tag | Use for |
|-----|---------|
| `@smoke` | Critical path / build-gate happy paths |
| `@sanity` | Broader confidence after smoke; still fast |
| `@regression` | Full functional coverage beyond smoke/sanity |
| `@api` | Contract / `request`-fixture API checks |
| `@e2e` | Multi-step UI journeys across pages |
| `@destructive` | **Only** tests that mutate shared/global state (locale, roles, feature flags, org settings) |

Rules:

- Tags go on the **test**, never on `describe`.
- A test that creates records and cleans up **only its own data** keeps its importance tag (`@smoke` / `@sanity` / …) — that is **not** `@destructive`.
- `@destructive` runs serially: `npm run test:destructive` (`--workers=1`).
- **Any** test that mutates shared/global state (whether tagged `@destructive` or temporarily changing settings inside another flow) **must** register an `afterEach` or `afterAll` revert hook that restores the prior value. Prefer capturing the previous state before mutate, then restore in the hook even on failure.

✅ **Good**

```ts
test('creates a program from the empty state', {
  tag: '@smoke',
}, async ({ page }) => {
  const program = buildProgram();
  // … create, assert, delete via api-cleanup — own data only → @smoke, not @destructive
});

test('switches org locale to fr-CA', {
  tag: '@destructive',
}, async ({ page }) => {
  const previous = await readOrgLocale(page);
  await setOrgLocale(page, 'fr-CA');
  // assertions…
  // revert is required — see afterEach below
});

test.afterEach(async ({ page }) => {
  await restoreOrgLocale(page); // always restore shared state
});
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
test.describe('programs', { tag: '@smoke' }, () => { /* … */ }); // tag on describe

test('toggles a feature flag', { tag: '@smoke' }, async ({ page }) => {
  await enableFlag(page, 'new-nav'); // shared state + wrong tag + no revert
});
```

**Why:** one tag keeps slices (`npm run test:smoke`, …) disjoint and greppable. `@destructive` is reserved for cross-test pollution risk; own-data CRUD stays on importance tags. Revert hooks make serial destructive runs safe for the next worker/job.

## 12. Test data — factories, curated invalid, env, enums

| Kind | Where | Rule |
|------|-------|------|
| Happy-path entities | `test-data/factories/*.factory.ts` | Faker-backed builders; unique per call; allow `overrides` |
| Invalid / edge inputs | `test-data/*.ts` static modules | Curated sets (too long, empty, XSS probes) — **not** random |
| Secrets & URLs | `process.env` | `DIDAXIS_URL`, credentials, tokens — never literals in specs |
| Repeated paths / messages | enums or const maps under `test-data/` or `support/` | No copy-pasted route strings or toast copy across specs |

✅ **Good — factory** (`test-data/factories/program.factory.ts`)

```ts
import { faker } from '@faker-js/faker';

export type ProgramInput = { name: string; description: string };

export function buildProgram(overrides: Partial<ProgramInput> = {}): ProgramInput {
  return {
    name: `QA ${faker.commerce.department()} ${faker.string.alphanumeric(6)}`,
    description: faker.lorem.sentence(),
    ...overrides,
  };
}

// in a spec:
const program = buildProgram();
const named = buildProgram({ name: 'Fixed Name For Assertion' });
```

✅ **Good — curated invalid + enum**

```ts
// test-data/invalid-program-names.ts
export const INVALID_PROGRAM_NAMES = ['', ' ', 'a'.repeat(256), '<script>'] as const;

// test-data/routes.ts
export enum AppRoute {
  Programs = '/programs',
  Settings = '/settings',
}
```

❌ **Bad**

```ts
const name = `Program ${Date.now()}`;           // prefer factory
await page.goto('https://test.didaxis.studio/programs'); // URL from env / baseURL
const password = 'SuperSecret123!';             // secret from process.env
await expect(page.getByText('Program created successfully')).toBeVisible();
// …same string duplicated in five specs → extract to an enum/const
```

**Why:** factories keep happy-path data unique and readable; curated invalid sets stay stable for negative tests; env keeps secrets out of git; enums kill drift when copy or paths change.

## Refusals (hard stops)

These are not preferences. If asked (or tempted) to do any of the following, **refuse**: stop, do not comply, and raise the conflict with the user or parent agent.

- **Never weaken or delete an assertion to make a test pass.** Escalate; do not "heal" expectations.
- **Never heal a failure triage classified as a real app bug.** Route to bug filing; do not patch the POM or spec to hide the defect.
- **Never replace a role-based locator with CSS or XPath.** Keep `getByRole` / `getByLabel` / `getByText` / `getByTestId`.
- **Never use `waitForTimeout`.** Prefer web-first assertions and event-driven waits.
- **Never hardcode a credential.** Use env / secrets only.
- **Never use the `any` type.** Type the locator, fixture, and API surfaces properly.
